{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Problem RoPE Solves"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sinusoidal and learned embeddings inject position information by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "adding"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " a position vector to the token embedding before the first layer. Position and token identity become entangled in a single vector and then pass through multiple projections. What attention really needs is for the dot product "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "q·k"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to depend on the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "relative offset"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " between positions, not their absolute indices. Rotary Position Embedding (RoPE), introduced by Su et al. (2021) in \"RoFormer\", achieves exactly this by rotating query and key vectors rather than adding to token embeddings."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Core Idea: Rotation Encodes Relative Position"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "RoPE treats each consecutive pair of dimensions (2i, 2i+1) in a query or key vector as a 2D plane and rotates that pair by an angle proportional to the token's position. The rotation angle for dimension pair i at position m is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\theta_i = \\frac{1}{10000^{2i/d_{\\text{model}}}}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For a query vector q at position m, the rotated query in dimension pair i is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\tilde{q}(m)_{2i} = q_{2i}\\cos(m\\theta_i) - q_{2i+1}\\sin(m\\theta_i)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\tilde{q}(m)_{2i+1} = q_{2i}\\sin(m\\theta_i) + q_{2i+1}\\cos(m\\theta_i)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The same rotation with angle "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "n·θᵢ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is applied to the key at position n. The critical property: the dot product of the rotated query and key depends only on the offset m − n:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\tilde{q}(m) \\cdot \\tilde{k}(n) = f(q, k, m - n)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "RoPE diagram showing query and key vectors rotated in a 2D dimension pair, with angle (m-n)θᵢ between them representing the relative offset, plus a comparison table against sinusoidal and learned PE"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Complex Number View"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The rotation is most cleanly written using complex numbers. Treat each dimension pair as one complex value:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "z_j = x_{2j} + i\\,x_{2j+1}, \\qquad \\tilde{z}_j(m) = z_j \\cdot e^{im\\theta_j}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The attention score between query at position m and key at position n is:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\operatorname{Re}\\!\\left(\\tilde{q}(m) \\cdot \\tilde{k}(n)^*\\right) = \\operatorname{Re}\\!\\left(q \\cdot k^* \\cdot e^{i(m-n)\\theta}\\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This makes the positional dependency exact: the score is a function of m − n, not m or n separately. In contrast, sinusoidal PE encodes absolute position and only "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "implicitly"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " makes relative positions learnable through the rotation matrix decomposition."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "PyTorch Implementation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nfrom typing import Tuple\n\nclass RotaryEmbedding(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, dim: int, base: int = 10000):\n        super().__init__()\n        # Compute θᵢ for i = 0, 2, 4, ..., dim-2\n        inv_freq = 1.0 / (base ** (torch.arange(0, dim, 2).float() / dim))\n        self.register_buffer('inv_freq', inv_freq)  # (dim/2,)\n\n    def forward(self, seq_len: int, device: torch.device) -> Tuple[torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor]:\n        # Position indices: (seq_len,)\n        t = torch.arange(seq_len, device=device).float()\n        # Outer product: (seq_len,) × (dim/2,) → (seq_len, dim/2)\n        freqs = torch.outer(t, self.inv_freq)\n        # Duplicate: (seq_len, dim)  — interleaved [θ₀, θ₀, θ₁, θ₁, ...]\n        emb = torch.cat([freqs, freqs], dim=-1)\n        return emb.cos(), emb.sin()\n\n\ndef rotate_half(x: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n    \"\"\"Rotate pairs: [x₀, x₁, x₂, x₃] → [−x₁, x₀, −x₃, x₂]\"\"\"\n    x1 = x[..., : x.shape[-1] // 2]   # first half\n    x2 = x[..., x.shape[-1] // 2 :]   # second half\n    return torch.cat([-x2, x1], dim=-1)\n\n\ndef apply_rotary_emb(\n    q: torch.Tensor, k: torch.Tensor,\n    cos: torch.Tensor, sin: torch.Tensor\n) -> Tuple[torch.Tensor, torch.Tensor]:\n    \"\"\"\n    q, k: (batch, heads, seq_len, head_dim)\n    cos, sin: (seq_len, head_dim)  — broadcast over batch and heads\n    \"\"\"\n    cos = cos.unsqueeze(0).unsqueeze(0)  # (1, 1, seq_len, head_dim)\n    sin = sin.unsqueeze(0).unsqueeze(0)\n    q_rot = q * cos + rotate_half(q) * sin\n    k_rot = k * cos + rotate_half(k) * sin\n    return q_rot, k_rot\n\n\n# Usage in a self-attention layer\nbatch, heads, seq_len, head_dim = 2, 8, 512, 64\nrope = RotaryEmbedding(dim=head_dim)\nq = torch.randn(batch, heads, seq_len, head_dim)\nk = torch.randn(batch, heads, seq_len, head_dim)\ncos_emb, sin_emb = rope(seq_len, device=q.device)\nq_rot, k_rot = apply_rotary_emb(q, k, cos_emb, sin_emb)\nprint(q_rot.shape)  # (2, 8, 512, 64) — same shape; only Q and K are rotated"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Where RoPE Applies Inside Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Unlike additive PE, RoPE does not touch the value vectors V or the token embeddings. It is applied "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "after"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " the linear projections W_Q and W_K, just before computing the attention scores:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\nclass RoPEAttention(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, num_heads: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.num_heads = num_heads\n        self.head_dim = d_model // num_heads\n        self.W_Q = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_K = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_V = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.W_O = nn.Linear(d_model, d_model, bias=False)\n        self.rope = RotaryEmbedding(self.head_dim)\n\n    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:\n        B, T, C = x.shape\n        q = self.W_Q(x).view(B, T, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).transpose(1, 2)\n        k = self.W_K(x).view(B, T, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).transpose(1, 2)\n        v = self.W_V(x).view(B, T, self.num_heads, self.head_dim).transpose(1, 2)\n\n        # Apply RoPE to Q and K only — V is unchanged\n        cos_emb, sin_emb = self.rope(T, device=x.device)\n        q, k = apply_rotary_emb(q, k, cos_emb, sin_emb)\n\n        # Standard scaled dot-product attention\n        scale = math.sqrt(self.head_dim)\n        attn = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(q, k, v, scale=1.0 / scale, is_causal=True)\n        attn = attn.transpose(1, 2).contiguous().view(B, T, C)\n        return self.W_O(attn)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Advantages Over Other PE Methods"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Exact relative position:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The dot product between rotated Q and K is a function of m − n by construction. Sinusoidal PE only enables relative position learning indirectly."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "No extra parameters:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Like sinusoidal PE, θᵢ values are fixed. Learned PE spends max_len × d_model parameters on position, which do not extrapolate."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Better long-context behaviour:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Because the score depends only on relative distance, the model can generalise to sequences longer than training length more gracefully than additive schemes. Extensions like YaRN and LongRoPE further improve this by rescaling the θᵢ frequencies."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Efficient implementation:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " The rotation is a pointwise multiply-and-add of precomputed sin/cos tables — no extra matrix multiplications required. Flash Attention supports RoPE natively."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Frequency Scaling for Longer Contexts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When models trained at context length L need to serve contexts of length L', the θᵢ values can be rescaled. The most common approaches are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Linear scaling:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Divide all positions by the scaling factor s = L' / L. Quick but degrades accuracy at long range."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "NTK-aware scaling:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Scale the base (e.g., 10000 → 500000) so that high-frequency dimensions are less distorted. Used by Code LLaMA and LLaMA 3."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "YaRN:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " Applies different scaling factors to different frequency bands — low-frequency dimensions are linearly scaled, high-frequency dimensions are left unchanged. Requires a short fine-tuning pass."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# NTK-aware base scaling for extended context\n# Original base = 10000, trained at 4096 tokens\n# Target context = 32768 tokens → scaling factor = 8\n\nscale = 32768 / 4096  # = 8.0\nnew_base = int(10000 * scale ** (64 / (64 - 2)))  # ≈ 500000 for d_head=64\n\nrope_extended = RotaryEmbedding(dim=64, base=new_base)\n# Now generate cos/sin for up to 32768 tokens — no fine-tuning needed for moderate extensions\ncos_ext, sin_ext = rope_extended(seq_len=32768, device='cpu')\nprint(cos_ext.shape)  # (32768, 64)"
          }
        ]
      },
